          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>
                                        <date>March 26/54</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>To</p>
                              <p>
                                        <sic>
                                                  <addressee>Isaacs Lesser Esqre</addressee>
                                        </sic>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>371 Walnut St. Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">I arrived in this city from
                                                  <placeName>Auburn</placeName><lb/> about two weeks
                                        back, have seen your agent<lb/>
                                        <persName>Mr C Myers</persName> who kindly give me the
                                        Occident<lb/> containing the portion of my letter.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I have used my endeavours in forwarding<lb/> your
                                                  <sic>enterpriseing</sic> work the Bible,
                                        which<lb/> I must say is a Credit to you, and trust<lb/>
                                        will prove productive for your labours.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">In regard to further Information<lb/> respecting
                                        the Jews in <placeName>China</placeName>, I have had an<lb/>
                                        Interview with <persName>Mr Spear</persName> of whom I spoke
                                        of<lb/> in my last, he <sic>his</sic> not the Gent who
                                        was<lb/> in <placeName>China</placeName> in my time, he has
                                        only been in<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Canton</placeName> three years and not out of it
                                        till he<lb/> come to this country, as he said to me we
                                        who<lb/> reside at <placeName>Canton</placeName> can have
                                        but little com-<lb/>-munication with the Chinese in
                                        consequence<lb/> of its being unsafe to go out into the
                                        streets, he<lb/> also says that he never heard or read of
                                        any such<lb/> sect as Jews &amp;c in
                                                  <placeName>China</placeName> he is only acquainted
                                        with<lb/> the Canton Dialect, in the Occident of
                                                  <date>January</date><lb/> Page 514 you propose to
                                        send a person duly qualified<lb/> to
                                                  <placeName>Shanghai</placeName> to open
                                        communication with<lb/> the people of
                                                  <placeName>Kai-fong-foo</placeName>, that
                                        proposition</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p><sic>his</sic> highly <sic>esential</sic> as that <hi
                                                  rend="underline">must</hi> be the first step. To
                                        begin about there to carry out the object in
                                        <add>?</add><lb/> then follow the plan of the
                                                  <sic>Jesuites</sic> which is to<lb/> establish
                                        posts of communications in every<lb/> district from
                                                  <placeName>Shanghai</placeName> to the place
                                                  <sic>wher</sic> our supp<lb/>-osed
                                                  <sic>Bretherin</sic> are to be found, this is to
                                        be done by<lb/> feeing<add>?</add> the officer of each
                                        district then they will<lb/> pass the letters of
                                                  <sic>corrospondance</sic>, and
                                        <sic>verry</sic><lb/> probable pass a <sic>foreignor</sic>
                                        through, as let a <sic>foreignor</sic><lb/> Disguise himself
                                        ever so much the Chinese can<lb/> Discover him, which if
                                        such should be the case<lb/> the officer of the district can
                                        torment him in a most<lb/> Barbarous manner for any length
                                        of time and<lb/> when he thinks proper he can send him
                                        back<lb/> through the same districts as he come to his
                                        first<lb/> starting place, and then the isolated
                                        Traveller<lb/> cannot have any redress from his
                                        Government,<lb/> a Little money works wonders among the
                                        China officials<lb/>
                                        <sic>therefor</sic> I am still of the same opinion that the<lb/>
                                        <sic>Obsticals</sic> are to be over come in
                                        communicating<lb/> with the people of
                                                  <placeName>Kai-fong-foo</placeName>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)"><sic>if</sic> the people in the
                                                  <placeName><sic>atlantic</sic></placeName> are
                                        going to send<lb/> out a mission and they have confidence
                                        enough<lb/> in me I should have no objection of being
                                        one<lb/> of the parties for that mission to
                                                  <placeName>Shanghai</placeName>, provided<lb/>
                                        that I was paid for going out there, any persons<lb/> which
                                        they may send if they should come by way<lb/> of
                                                  <placeName>California</placeName> I shall be most
                                        happy to give them<lb/> all the information that lays in my
                                        power as with<lb/> one hour conversation with them I should
                                        be able</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>to enlighten them more than writing six sheets of<lb/> paper full
                                        about <placeName>China</placeName>. Questions would
                                        bring<lb/> things to my memory <sic>wher</sic> other wise I
                                        cannot<lb/> think of them and I would not have any
                                        thing<lb/> which I may write or repeat go before the
                                        public<lb/> but that which I know to be the Truth.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I will conclude by wishing you<lb/> every success
                                        in your undertakings<lb/> &amp; <sic>Belive</sic> me to be
                                        yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">
                                        <persName role="author">Samuel H. Cohen</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>care of <persName>B Keesing</persName>
                                        <placeName>Box 488 Post Office</placeName></p>
